# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: uefi-secure-boot-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] In computing, **BIOS** or the **Basic Input/Output System** is a type of firmware used to provide runtime services for operating systems and programs and to perform hardware initialization during the booting process (power-on startup).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] On a computer using BIOS firmware, the firmware comes pre-installed on the computer's motherboard.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The name originates from the **B**asic **I**nput/**O**utput **S**ystem used in the CP/M operating system in 1975.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The BIOS firmware was originally proprietary to the IBM PC; it was reverse engineered by some companies, such as Compaq, Phoenix Technologies, AMI and others, looking to create compatible systems.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The interface of that original system serves as a *de facto* standard.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The BIOS in older PCs initializes and tests the system hardware components (power-on self-test or POST for short), and loads a boot loader from a mass storage device which then initializes a kernel.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] In the era of DOS, the BIOS provided BIOS interrupt calls for the keyboard, display, storage, and other input/output (I/O) devices that standardized an interface to application programs and the operating system.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] More recent operating systems do not use the BIOS interrupt calls after startup.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Most BIOS implementations are specifically designed to work with a particular computer or motherboard model, by interfacing with various devices especially system chipset.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Originally, BIOS firmware was stored in a ROM chip on the PC motherboard.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] In later computer systems, the BIOS contents are stored on flash memory so it can be rewritten without removing the chip from the motherboard.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] This allows easy, end-user updates to the BIOS firmware so new features can be added or bugs can be fixed, but it also creates a possibility for the computer to become infected with BIOS rootkits.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Furthermore, a BIOS upgrade that fails could brick the motherboard.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) is a successor to the legacy PC BIOS, aiming to address its technical limitations.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] UEFI firmware may include legacy BIOS compatibility to maintain compatibility with operating systems and option cards that do not support UEFI native operation.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Intel phased out providing support for booting from the BIOS interface from 2020 to 2024 depending on the platform.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The last version of Microsoft Windows to officially support running on PCs which use legacy BIOS firmware is Windows 10 as Windows 11 requires a UEFI-compliant system (except for IoT Enterprise editions of Windows 11 since version 24H2).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The term BIOS (Basic Input/Output System) was created by Gary Kildall and first appeared in the CP/M operating system in 1975, describing the machine-specific part of CP/M loaded during boot time that interfaces directly with the hardware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Versions of MS-DOS, PC DOS or DR-DOS contain a file called variously "IO.SYS", "IBMBIO.COM", "IBMBIO.SYS", or "DRBIOS.SYS"; this file is known as the "DOS BIOS" (also known as the "DOS I/O System") and contains the lower-level hardware-specific part of the operating system.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Together with the underlying hardware-specific but operating system-independent "System BIOS", which resides in ROM, it represents the analogue to the "CP/M BIOS".
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The BIOS originally proprietary to the IBM PC has been reverse engineered by some companies, such as Compaq, Phoenix Technologies, AMI and others, looking to create compatible systems.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] With the introduction of PS/2 machines, IBM divided the System BIOS into real- and protected-mode portions.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The BIOS of the original IBM PC and XT had no interactive user interface.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Error codes or messages were displayed on the screen, or coded series of sounds were generated to signal errors when the power-on self-test (POST) had not proceeded to the point of successfully initializing a video display adapter.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Options on the IBM PC and XT were set by switches and jumpers on the main board and on expansion cards.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Starting around the mid-1990s, it became typical for the BIOS ROM to include a *"BIOS configuration utility"* (BCU) or "BIOS setup utility", accessed at system power-up by a particular key sequence.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] This program allowed the user to set system configuration options, of the type formerly set using DIP switches, through an interactive menu system controlled through the keyboard.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] In the interim period, IBM-compatible PCs‍—‌including the IBM AT‍—‌held configuration settings in battery-backed RAM and used a bootable configuration program on floppy disk, not in the ROM, to set the configuration options contained in this memory.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The floppy disk was supplied with the computer, and if it was lost the system settings could not be changed.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The same applied in general to computers with an EISA bus, for which the configuration program was called an EISA Configuration Utility (ECU).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] A modern Wintel-compatible computer provides a setup routine essentially unchanged in nature from the ROM-resident BIOS setup utilities of the late 1990s; the user can configure hardware options using the keyboard and video display.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The modern Wintel machine may store the BIOS configuration settings in flash ROM, perhaps the same flash ROM that holds the BIOS itself.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Peripheral cards such as hard disk drive host bus adapters and video cards have their own firmware, and BIOS extension option ROM code may be a part of the expansion card firmware; that code provides additional capabilities in the BIOS.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Code in option ROMs runs before the BIOS boots the operating system from mass storage.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] These ROMs typically test and initialize hardware, add new BIOS services, or replace existing BIOS services with their own services.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] For example, a SCSI controller usually has a BIOS extension ROM that adds support for hard drives connected through that controller.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] An extension ROM could in principle contain operating system, or it could implement an entirely different boot process such as network booting.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Operation of an IBM-compatible computer system can be completely changed by removing or inserting an adapter card (or a ROM chip) that contains a BIOS extension ROM.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The motherboard BIOS typically contains code for initializing and bootstrapping integrated display and integrated storage.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] In addition, plug-in adapter cards such as SCSI, RAID, network interface cards, and video cards often include their own BIOS (e.g., Video BIOS), complementing or replacing the system BIOS code for the given component.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Even devices built into the motherboard can behave in this way; their option ROMs can be a part of the motherboard BIOS.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] An add-in card requires an option ROM if the card is not supported by the motherboard BIOS and the card needs to be initialized or made accessible through BIOS services before the operating system can be loaded (usually this means it is required in the boot process).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] An additional advantage of ROM on some early PC systems (notably including the IBM PCjr) was that ROM was faster than main system RAM.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Option ROMs normally reside on adapter cards.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The IBM PCjr is unique among PCs in having two ROM cartridge slots on the front.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Cartridges in these slots map into the same region of the upper memory area used for option ROMs, and the cartridges can contain option ROM modules that the BIOS would recognize.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The cartridges can also contain other types of ROM modules, such as BASIC programs, that are handled differently.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] One PCjr cartridge can contain several ROM modules of different types, possibly stored together in one ROM chip.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The 8086 and 8088 start at physical address FFFF0h.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The 80286 starts at physical address FFFFF0h.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The 80386 and later x86 processors start at physical address FFFFFFF0h.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] When the system is initialized, the first instruction of the BIOS appears at that address.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] If the system has just been powered up or the reset button was pressed ("cold boot"), the full power-on self-test (POST) is run.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] If Ctrl+Alt+Delete was pressed ("warm boot"), a special flag value stored in nonvolatile BIOS memory ("CMOS") tested by the BIOS allows bypass of the lengthy POST and memory detection.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The POST identifies, tests and initializes system devices such as the CPU, chipset, RAM, motherboard, video card, keyboard, mouse, hard disk drive, optical disc drive and other hardware, including integrated peripherals.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Early IBM PCs had a routine in the POST that would download a program into RAM through the keyboard port and run it.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] This feature was intended for factory test or diagnostic purposes.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] After the motherboard BIOS completes its POST, most BIOS versions search for option ROM modules, also called BIOS extension ROMs, and execute them.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The motherboard BIOS scans for extension ROMs in a portion of the "upper memory area" (the part of the x86 real-mode address space at and above address 0xA0000) and runs each ROM found, in order.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] To discover memory-mapped option ROMs, a BIOS implementation scans the real-mode address space from `0x0C0000` to `0x0F0000` on 2 KB (2,048 bytes) boundaries, looking for a two-byte ROM *signature*: 0x55 followed by 0xAA.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] In a valid expansion ROM, this signature is followed by a single byte indicating the number of 512-byte blocks the expansion ROM occupies in real memory, and the next byte is the option ROM's entry point (also known as its "entry offset").
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] If the ROM has a valid checksum, the BIOS transfers control to the entry address, which in a normal BIOS extension ROM should be the beginning of the extension's initialization routine.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] At this point, the extension ROM code takes over, typically testing and initializing the hardware it controls and registering interrupt vectors for use by post-boot applications.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] It may use BIOS services (including those provided by previously initialized option ROMs) to provide a user configuration interface, to display diagnostic information, or to do anything else that it requires.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] An option ROM should normally return to the BIOS after completing its initialization process.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Once (and if) an option ROM returns, the BIOS continues searching for more option ROMs, calling each as it is found, until the entire option ROM area in the memory space has been scanned.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] It is possible that an option ROM will not return to BIOS, pre-empting the BIOS's boot sequence altogether.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] After the POST completes and, in a BIOS that supports option ROMs, after the option ROM scan is completed and all detected ROM modules with valid checksums have been called, the BIOS calls interrupt 19h to start boot processing.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Post-boot, programs loaded can also call interrupt 19h to reboot the system, but they must be careful to disable interrupts and other asynchronous hardware processes that may interfere with the BIOS rebooting process, or else the system may hang or crash while it is rebooting.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] When interrupt 19h is called, the BIOS attempts to locate boot loader software on a "boot device", such as a hard disk, a floppy disk, CD, or DVD.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] It loads and executes the first boot software it finds, giving it control of the PC.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The BIOS uses the boot devices set in Nonvolatile BIOS memory (CMOS), or, in the earliest PCs, DIP switches.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The BIOS checks each device in order to see if it is bootable by attempting to load the first sector (boot sector).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] If the sector cannot be read, the BIOS proceeds to the next device.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] If the sector is read successfully, some BIOSes will also check for the boot sector signature 0x55 0xAA in the last two bytes of the sector (which is 512 bytes long), before accepting a boot sector and considering the device bootable.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] When a bootable device is found, the BIOS transfers control to the loaded sector.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The BIOS does not interpret the contents of the boot sector other than to possibly check for the boot sector signature in the last two bytes.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Interpretation of data structures like partition tables and BIOS Parameter Blocks is done by the boot program in the boot sector itself or by other programs loaded through the boot process.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] A non-disk device such as a network adapter attempts booting by a procedure that is defined by its option ROM or the equivalent integrated into the motherboard BIOS ROM.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] As such, option ROMs may also influence or supplant the boot process defined by the motherboard BIOS ROM.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] With the El Torito optical media boot standard, the optical drive actually emulates a 3.5" high-density floppy disk to the BIOS for boot purposes.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Reading the "first sector" of a CD-ROM or DVD-ROM is not a simply defined operation like it is on a floppy disk or a hard disk.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Furthermore, the complexity of the medium makes it difficult to write a useful boot program in one sector.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The bootable virtual floppy disk can contain software that provides access to the optical medium in its native format.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] If an expansion ROM wishes to change the way the system boots (such as from a network device or a SCSI adapter) in a cooperative way, it can use the *BIOS Boot Specification* (BBS) API to register its ability to do so.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Once the expansion ROMs have registered using the BBS APIs, the user can select among the available boot options from within the BIOS's user interface.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] This is why most BBS compliant PC BIOS implementations will not allow the user to enter the BIOS's user interface until the expansion ROMs have finished executing and registering themselves with the BBS API.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Also, if an expansion ROM wishes to change the way the system boots unilaterally, it can simply hook interrupt 19h or other interrupts normally called from interrupt 19h, such as interrupt 13h, the BIOS disk service, to intercept the BIOS boot process.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Then it can replace the BIOS boot process with one of its own, or it can merely modify the boot sequence by inserting its own boot actions into it, by preventing the BIOS from detecting certain devices as bootable, or both.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Before the BIOS Boot Specification was promulgated, this was the only way for expansion ROMs to implement boot capability for devices not supported for booting by the native BIOS of the motherboard.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The user can select the boot priority implemented by the BIOS.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] For example, most computers have a hard disk that is bootable, but sometimes there is a removable-media drive that has higher boot priority, so the user can cause a removable disk to be booted.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] In most modern BIOSes, the boot priority order can be configured by the user.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The BIOS in an early PC also usually would only boot from the first floppy disk drive or the first hard disk drive, even if there were two drives installed.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] On the original IBM PC and XT, if no bootable disk was found, the BIOS would try to start ROM BASIC with the interrupt call to interrupt 18h.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Since few programs used BASIC in ROM, clone PC makers left it out; then a computer that failed to boot from a disk would display "No ROM BASIC" and halt (in response to interrupt 18h).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Later computers would display a message like "No bootable disk found"; some would prompt for a disk to be inserted and a key to be pressed to retry the boot process.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] A modern BIOS may display nothing or may automatically enter the BIOS configuration utility when the boot process fails.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The environment for the boot program is very simple: the CPU is in real mode and the general-purpose and segment registers are undefined, except SS, SP, CS, and DL.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] CS:IP always points to physical address `0x07C00`.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] What values CS and IP actually have is not well defined.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Because boot programs are always loaded at this fixed address, there is no need for a boot program to be relocatable.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] DL may contain the drive number, as used with interrupt 13h, of the boot device.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] SS:SP points to a valid stack that is presumably large enough to support hardware interrupts, but otherwise SS and SP are undefined.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] (A stack must be already set up in order for interrupts to be serviced, and interrupts must be enabled in order for the system timer-tick interrupt, which BIOS always uses at least to maintain the time-of-day count and which it initializes during POST, to be active and for the keyboard to work.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] At boot time, all BIOS services are available, and the memory below address `0x00400` contains the interrupt vector table.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] BIOS POST has initialized the system timers, interrupt controller(s), DMA controller(s), and other motherboard/chipset hardware as necessary to bring all BIOS services to ready status.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] DRAM refresh for all system DRAM in conventional memory and extended memory, but not necessarily expanded memory, has been set up and is running.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The BIOS maintains a reserved block of system RAM at addresses `0x00400–0x004FF` with various parameters initialized during the POST.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] All memory at and above address `0x00500` can be used by the boot program; it may even overwrite itself.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The BIOS ROM is customized to the particular manufacturer's hardware, allowing low-level services (such as reading a keystroke or writing a sector of data to diskette) to be provided in a standardized way to programs, including operating systems.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] For example, an IBM PC might have either a monochrome or a color display adapter (using different display memory addresses and hardware), but a single, standard, BIOS system call may be invoked to display a character at a specified position on the screen in text mode or graphics mode.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The BIOS provides a small library of basic input/output functions to operate peripherals (such as the keyboard, rudimentary text and graphics display functions and so forth).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Operating systems and executive software that are designed to supersede this basic firmware functionality provide replacement software interfaces to application software.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Applications can also provide these services to themselves.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] This began even in the 1980s under MS-DOS, when programmers observed that using the BIOS video services for graphics display were very slow.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] To increase the speed of screen output, many programs bypassed the BIOS and programmed the video display hardware directly.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Other graphics programmers, particularly but not exclusively in the demoscene, observed that there were technical capabilities of the PC display adapters that were not supported by the IBM BIOS and could not be taken advantage of without circumventing it.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Since the AT-compatible BIOS ran in Intel real mode, operating systems that ran in protected mode on 286 and later processors required hardware device drivers compatible with protected mode operation to replace BIOS services.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Modern operating systems, such as Windows and Linux, use the BIOS interrupt calls only during the booting process.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Before the operating system's first graphical screen is displayed, input and output are typically handled through BIOS.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] A boot menu such as the textual menu of Windows, which allows users to choose an operating system to boot, to boot into the safe mode, or to use the last known good configuration, is displayed through BIOS and receives keyboard input through BIOS.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Many modern PCs can still boot and run legacy operating systems such as MS-DOS or DR-DOS that rely heavily on BIOS for their console and disk I/O, providing that the system has a BIOS, or a CSM-capable UEFI firmware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Intel processors have reprogrammable microcode since the P6 microarchitecture.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] AMD processors have reprogrammable microcode since the K7 microarchitecture.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The BIOS contains patches to the processor microcode that fix errors in the initial processor microcode; microcode is loaded into processor's SRAM so reprogramming is not persistent, thus loading of microcode updates is performed each time the system is powered up.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Without reprogrammable microcode, an expensive processor swap would be required; for example, the Pentium FDIV bug became an expensive fiasco for Intel as it required a product recall because the original Pentium processor's defective microcode could not be reprogrammed.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Operating systems can also update the microcode.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Some BIOSes contain a software licensing description table (SLIC), a digital signature placed inside the BIOS by the original equipment manufacturer (OEM), for example Dell.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The SLIC is inserted into the ACPI data table and contains no active code.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Computer manufacturers that distribute OEM versions of Microsoft Windows and Microsoft application software can use the SLIC to authenticate licensing to the OEM Windows Installation disk and system recovery disc containing Windows software.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Systems with a SLIC can be preactivated with an OEM product key, and they verify an XML formatted OEM certificate against the SLIC in the BIOS as a means of self-activating (see System Locked Preinstallation, SLP).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] If a user performs a fresh install of Windows, they will need to have possession of both the OEM key (either SLP or COA) and the digital certificate for their SLIC in order to bypass activation.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] This can be achieved if the user performs a restore using a pre-customised image provided by the OEM.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Power users can copy the necessary certificate files from the OEM image, decode the SLP product key, then perform SLP activation manually.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Some BIOS implementations allow overclocking, an action in which the CPU is adjusted to a higher clock rate than its manufacturer rating for guaranteed capability.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Overclocking may, however, seriously compromise system reliability in insufficiently cooled computers and generally shorten component lifespan.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Overclocking, when incorrectly performed, may also cause components to overheat so quickly that they mechanically destroy themselves.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Some older operating systems, for example MS-DOS, rely on the BIOS to carry out most input/output tasks within the PC.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Calling real mode BIOS services directly is inefficient for protected mode (and long mode) operating systems.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] BIOS interrupt calls are not used by modern multitasking operating systems after they initially load.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] In the 1990s, BIOS provided some protected mode interfaces for Microsoft Windows and Unix-like operating systems, such as Advanced Power Management (APM), Plug and Play BIOS, Desktop Management Interface (DMI), VESA BIOS Extensions (VBE), e820 and MultiProcessor Specification (MPS).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Starting from the year 2000, most BIOSes provide ACPI, SMBIOS, VBE and e820 interfaces for modern operating systems.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] After operating systems load, the System Management Mode code is still running in SMRAM.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Since 2010, BIOS technology is in a transitional process toward UEFI.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Historically, the BIOS in the IBM PC and XT had no built-in user interface.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The BIOS versions in earlier PCs (XT-class) were not software configurable; instead, users set the options via DIP switches on the motherboard.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Later computers, including most IBM-compatibles with 80286 CPUs, had a battery-backed nonvolatile BIOS memory (CMOS RAM chip) that held BIOS settings.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] These settings, such as video-adapter type, memory size, and hard-disk parameters, could only be configured by running a configuration program from a disk, not built into the ROM.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] A special "reference diskette" was inserted in an IBM AT to configure settings such as memory size.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Early BIOS versions did not have passwords or boot-device selection options.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The BIOS was hard-coded to boot from the first floppy drive, or, if that failed, the first hard disk.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Access control in early AT-class machines was by a physical keylock switch (which was not hard to defeat if the computer case could be opened).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Anyone who could switch on the computer could boot it.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Later, 386-class computers started integrating the BIOS setup utility in the ROM itself, alongside the BIOS code; these computers usually boot into the BIOS setup utility if a certain key or key combination is pressed, otherwise the BIOS POST and boot process are executed.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] A modern BIOS setup utility has a text user interface (TUI) or graphical user interface (GUI) accessed by pressing a certain key on the keyboard when the PC starts.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Usually, the key is advertised for short time during the early startup, for example "Press DEL to enter Setup".
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The actual key depends on specific hardware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The settings key is most often Delete (Acer, ASRock, Asus PC, ECS, Gigabyte, MSI, Zotac) and F2 (Asus motherboard, Dell, Lenovo laptop, Origin PC, Samsung, Toshiba), but it can also be F1 (Lenovo desktop) and F10 (HP).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] A modern BIOS setup screen often features a **PC Health Status** or a **Hardware Monitoring** tab, which directly interfaces with a Hardware Monitor chip of the mainboard.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] This makes it possible to monitor CPU and chassis temperature, the voltage provided by the power supply unit, as well as monitor and control the speed of the fans connected to the motherboard.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Some operating systems, like NetBSD with envsys and OpenBSD with sysctl hw.sensors, feature integrated interfacing with hardware monitors.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] However, in some circumstances, the BIOS also provides the underlying information about hardware monitoring through ACPI, in which case, the operating system may be using ACPI to perform hardware monitoring.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] In modern PCs the BIOS is stored in rewritable EEPROM or NOR flash memory, allowing the contents to be replaced and modified.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] This rewriting of the contents is sometimes termed *flashing.* It can be done by a special program, usually provided by the system's manufacturer, or at POST, with a BIOS image in a hard drive or USB flash drive.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] A file containing such contents is sometimes termed "a BIOS image".
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] A BIOS might be reflashed in order to upgrade to a newer version to fix bugs or provide improved performance or to support newer hardware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Some computers also support updating the BIOS via an update floppy disk or a special partition on the hard drive.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The original IBM PC BIOS (and cassette BASIC) was stored on mask-programmed read-only memory (ROM) chips in sockets on the motherboard.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] ROMs could be replaced, but not altered, by users.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] To allow for updates, many compatible computers used re-programmable BIOS memory devices such as EPROM, EEPROM and later flash memory (usually NOR flash) devices.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] According to Robert Braver, the president of the BIOS manufacturer Micro Firmware, **Flash BIOS** chips became common around 1995 because the electrically erasable PROM (EEPROM) chips are cheaper and easier to program than standard ultraviolet erasable PROM (EPROM) chips.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Flash chips are programmed (and re-programmed) in-circuit, while EPROM chips need to be removed from the motherboard for re-programming.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] BIOS versions are upgraded to take advantage of newer versions of hardware and to correct bugs in previous revisions of BIOSes.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Beginning with the IBM AT, PCs supported a hardware clock settable through BIOS.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] It had a century bit which allowed for manually changing the century when the year 2000 happened.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Most BIOS revisions created in 1995 and nearly all BIOS revisions in 1997 supported the year 2000 by setting the century bit automatically when the clock rolled past midnight, 31 December 1999.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The first flash chips were attached to the ISA bus.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Starting in 1998, the BIOS flash moved to the LPC bus, following a new standard implementation known as "firmware hub" (FWH).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] In 2005, the BIOS flash memory moved to the SPI bus.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The size of the BIOS, and the capacity of the ROM, EEPROM, or other media it may be stored on, has increased over time as new features have been added to the code; BIOS versions now exist with sizes up to 32 megabytes.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] For contrast, the original IBM PC BIOS was contained in an 8 KB mask ROM.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Some modern motherboards are including even bigger NAND flash memory ICs on board which are capable of storing whole compact operating systems, such as some Linux distributions.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] For example, some ASUS notebooks included Splashtop OS embedded into their NAND flash memory ICs.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] However, the idea of including an operating system along with BIOS in the ROM of a PC is not new; in the 1980s, Microsoft offered a ROM option for MS-DOS, and it was included in the ROMs of some PC clones such as the Tandy 1000 HX.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Another type of firmware chip was found on the IBM PC AT and early compatibles.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] In the AT, the keyboard interface was controlled by a microcontroller with its own programmable memory.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] On the IBM AT, that was a 40-pin socketed device, while some manufacturers used an EPROM version of this chip which resembled an EPROM.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] This controller was also assigned the A20 gate function to manage memory above the one-megabyte range; occasionally an upgrade of this "keyboard BIOS" was necessary to take advantage of software that could use upper memory.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The BIOS may contain components such as the Memory Reference Code (MRC), which is responsible for the memory initialization (e.g.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Modern BIOS includes Intel Management Engine or AMD Platform Security Processor firmware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] IBM published full listings of the BIOSes for its original PC, PC XT, PC AT, and other contemporary PC models, in an appendix of the *IBM PC Technical Reference Manual* for each machine type.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] A benefit of the publication of the BIOS listings is that users could see exactly what the BIOS does and how it does it.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] However, those BIOSes were still copyright by IBM, so they could not be used by other manufacturers.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] In March 1983, Compaq released its Compaq Portable, which included a clean-room engineered BIOS.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] This made Compaq became the first company that cloned an IBM PC successfully.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] However, Compaq did not offer their BIOS to other computer manufacturers.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] In May 1984, Phoenix Software Associates released its first ROM-BIOS.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] This BIOS enabled OEMs to build essentially fully compatible clones without having to reverse-engineer the IBM PC BIOS themselves, as Compaq had done for the Portable; it also helped fuel the growth in the PC-compatibles industry and sales of non-IBM versions of DOS.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The first American Megatrends (AMI) BIOS was released in 1986.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] New standards grafted onto the BIOS are usually without complete public documentation or any BIOS listings.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] As a result, it is not as easy to learn the intimate details about the many non-IBM additions to BIOS as about the core BIOS services.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Many PC motherboard suppliers licensed the BIOS "core" and toolkit from a commercial third party, known as an "independent BIOS vendor" or IBV.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The motherboard manufacturer then customized this BIOS to suit its own hardware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] For this reason, updated BIOSes are normally obtained directly from the motherboard manufacturer.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Major IBVs included American Megatrends (AMI), Insyde Software, Phoenix Technologies, and Byosoft.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Microid Research and Award Software were acquired by Phoenix Technologies in 1998; Phoenix later phased out the Award brand name (although Award Software is still credited in AwardBIOS versions until 2001–2002, and AWRDACPI is still credited in Phoenix UEFI firmwares until late 2012).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] General Software, which was also acquired by Phoenix in 2007, sold BIOS for embedded systems based on Intel processors.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] SeaBIOS is an open-source BIOS implementation.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The open-source community increased their effort to develop a replacement for proprietary BIOSes and their future incarnations with open-sourced counterparts.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Open Firmware was an early attempt to make an open specification for boot firmware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] It was initially endorsed by IEEE in its *IEEE 1275-1994* standard but was withdrawn in 2005.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Later examples include the OpenBIOS, coreboot and libreboot projects.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] AMD provided product specifications for some chipsets using coreboot, and Google is sponsoring the project.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Motherboard manufacturer Tyan offers coreboot next to the standard BIOS with their Opteron line of motherboards.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] EEPROM and flash memory chips are advantageous because they can be easily updated by the user; it is customary for hardware manufacturers to issue BIOS updates to upgrade their products, improve compatibility and remove bugs.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] However, this advantage had the risk that an improperly executed or aborted BIOS update could render the computer or device unusable.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] To avoid these situations, more recent BIOSes use a "boot block"; a portion of the BIOS which runs first and must be updated separately.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] This code verifies if the rest of the BIOS is intact (using hash checksums or other methods) before transferring control to it.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] If the boot block detects any corruption in the main BIOS, it will typically warn the user that a recovery process must be initiated by booting from removable media (floppy, CD or USB flash drive) so the user can try flashing the BIOS again.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Some motherboards have a *backup* BIOS (sometimes referred as DualBIOS) to recover from BIOS corruptions, and they use a special PLC to do BIOS recovery from BIOS corruptions.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] There are at least five known viruses that attack the BIOS, two of which were for demonstration purposes.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The first one found in the wild was *Mebromi*, targeting Chinese users.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The first BIOS virus was BIOS Meningitis, which instead of erasing BIOS chips it infected them.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] BIOS Meningitis was relatively harmless, compared to a virus like CIH.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The second BIOS virus was CIH, also known as the "Chernobyl Virus", which was able to erase flash ROM BIOS content on compatible chipsets.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] CIH appeared in mid-1998 and became active in April 1999.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Often, infected computers could no longer boot, and people had to remove the flash ROM IC from the motherboard and reprogram it.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] CIH targeted the then-widespread Intel i430TX motherboard chipset and took advantage of the fact that the Windows 9x operating systems, also widespread at the time, allowed direct hardware access to all programs.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Modern systems are not vulnerable to CIH because of a variety of chipsets being used which are incompatible with the Intel i430TX chipset, and also other flash ROM IC types.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] There is also extra protection from accidental BIOS rewrites in the form of boot blocks which are protected from accidental overwrite or dual BIOS equipped systems which may, in the event of a crash, use a backup BIOS.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Also, all modern operating systems such as FreeBSD, Linux, macOS, Windows NT-based Windows OS like Windows 2000, Windows XP and newer, do not allow user-mode programs to have direct hardware access using a hardware abstraction layer.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] As a result, as of 2008, CIH has become essentially harmless, at worst causing annoyance by infecting executable files and triggering antivirus software.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Other BIOS viruses remain possible, however; since most Windows home users without Windows Vista/7's UAC run all applications with administrative privileges, a modern CIH-like virus could in principle still gain access to hardware without first using an exploit.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The operating system OpenBSD prevents all users from having this access and the grsecurity patch for the Linux kernel also prevents this direct hardware access by default, the difference being an attacker requiring a much more difficult kernel level exploit or reboot of the machine.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The third BIOS virus was a technique presented by John Heasman, principal security consultant for UK-based Next-Generation Security Software.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] In 2006, at the Black Hat Security Conference, he showed how to elevate privileges and read physical memory, using malicious procedures that replaced normal ACPI functions stored in flash memory.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The fourth BIOS virus was a technique called "Persistent BIOS infection." It appeared in 2009 at the CanSecWest Security Conference in Vancouver, and at the SyScan Security Conference in Singapore.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Researchers Anibal Sacco and Alfredo Ortega, from Core Security Technologies, demonstrated how to insert malicious code into the decompression routines in the BIOS, allowing for nearly full control of the PC at start-up, even before the operating system is booted.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The proof-of-concept does not exploit a flaw in the BIOS implementation, but only involves the normal BIOS flashing procedures.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Thus, it requires physical access to the machine, or for the user to be root.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Despite these requirements, Ortega underlined the profound implications of his and Sacco's discovery: "We can patch a driver to drop a fully working rootkit.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Mebromi is a trojan which targets computers with AwardBIOS, Microsoft Windows, and antivirus software from two Chinese companies: Rising Antivirus and Jiangmin KV Antivirus.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Mebromi installs a rootkit which infects the Master boot record.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] In a December 2013 interview with *60 Minutes*, Deborah Plunkett, Information Assurance Director for the US National Security Agency claimed the NSA had uncovered and thwarted a possible BIOS attack by a foreign nation state, targeting the US financial system.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The program cited anonymous sources alleging it was a Chinese plot.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] However follow-up articles in *The Guardian,* *The Atlantic,* *Wired* and *The Register* refuted the NSA's claims.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Newer Intel platforms have Intel Boot Guard (IBG) technology enabled, this technology will check the BIOS digital signature at startup, and the IBG public key is fused into the PCH.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) supplements the BIOS in many new machines.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Initially written for the Intel Itanium architecture, UEFI is now available for x86 and Arm platforms; the specification development is driven by the Unified EFI Forum, an industry special interest group.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] EFI booting has been supported in only Microsoft Windows versions supporting GPT, the Linux kernel 2.6.1 and later, and macOS on Intel-based Macs.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] As of 2014, new PC hardware predominantly ships with UEFI firmware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] The architecture of the rootkit safeguard can also prevent the system from running the user's own software changes, which makes UEFI controversial as a legacy BIOS replacement in the open hardware community.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] UEFI is required for devices shipping with Windows 8 and above.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Likewise, Windows 11 requires UEFI to boot, with the exception of IoT Enterprise editions of Windows 11.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] After the popularity of UEFI in 2010s, the older BIOS that supported BIOS interrupt calls was renamed to "legacy BIOS".
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Other alternatives to the functionality of the "Legacy BIOS" in the x86 world include coreboot and libreboot.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Some servers and workstations use a platform-independent Open Firmware (IEEE-1275) based on the Forth programming language; it is included with Sun's SPARC computers, IBM's RS/6000 line, and other PowerPC systems such as the CHRP motherboards, along with the x86-based OLPC XO-1.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] As of at least 2015, Apple has removed legacy BIOS support from the UEFI monitor in Intel-based Macs.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] As such, the BIOS utility no longer supports the legacy option, and prints "Legacy mode not supported on this system".
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] In 2017, Intel announced that it would remove legacy BIOS support by 2020.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/bios] Since 2019, new Intel platform OEM PCs no longer support the legacy option.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] This may be done by hardware or firmware in the CPU, or by a separate processor in the computer system.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] On some systems, a power-on reset (POR) does not initiate booting, and the operator must initiate booting after POR completes.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] IBM uses the term **Initial Program Load** (**IPL**) on some product lines.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Restarting a computer is also called *rebooting*, which can be "hard", e.g., after electrical power to the CPU is switched from off to on, or "soft", where the power is not cut.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] On some systems, a soft boot may optionally clear RAM to zero.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Both hard and soft booting can be initiated by hardware, such as a button press, or by a software command.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Booting is complete when the operative runtime system, typically the operating system and some applications, is attained.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The process of returning a computer from a state of sleep (suspension) does not involve booting; however, restoring it from a state of hibernation does.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Minimally, some embedded systems do not require a noticeable boot sequence to begin functioning, and when turned on, may simply run operational programs that are stored in read-only memory (ROM).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] All computing systems are state machines, and a reboot may be the only method to return to a designated zero-state from an unintended, locked state.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] In addition to loading an operating system or stand-alone utility, the boot process can also load a storage dump program for diagnosing problems in an operating system.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The earliest known recorded use of "boot" as the shortened form for "bootstrap" is 1975.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] There are many different methods available to load a short initial program into a computer.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] These methods range from simple, physical input to removable media that can hold more complex programs.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Early computers in the 1940s and 1950s were one-of-a-kind engineering efforts that could take weeks to program, and program loading was one of many problems that had to be solved.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] An early computer, ENIAC, had no program stored in memory but was set up for each problem by a configuration of interconnecting cables.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Bootstrapping did not apply to ENIAC, whose hardware configuration was ready for solving problems as soon as power was applied.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The EDSAC system, the second stored-program computer to be built, used stepping switches to transfer a fixed program into memory when its start button was pressed.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The program stored on this device, which David Wheeler completed in late 1948, loaded further instructions from punched tape and then executed them.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The first programmable computers for commercial sale, such as the UNIVAC I and the IBM 701 included features to make their operation simpler.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] They typically included instructions that performed a complete input or output operation.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The same hardware logic could be used to load the contents of a punch card (the most typical ones) or other input media, such as a magnetic drum or magnetic tape, that contained a bootstrap program by pressing a single button.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] This booting concept was called a variety of names for IBM computers of the 1950s and early 1960s, but IBM used the term "Initial Program Load" with the IBM 7030 Stretch and later used it for their mainframe lines, starting with the System/360 in 1964.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The IBM 701 computer (1952–1956) had a "Load" button that initiated reading of the first 36-bit word into main memory from a punched card in a card reader, a magnetic tape in a tape drive, or a magnetic drum unit, depending on the position of the Load Selector switch.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The left 18-bit half-word was then executed as an instruction, which usually read additional words into memory.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The loaded boot program was then executed, which, in turn, loaded a larger program from that medium into memory without further help from the human operator.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The IBM 704, IBM 7090, and IBM 7094 had similar mechanisms, but with different load buttons for different devices.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The term "boot" has been used in this sense since at least 1958.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Other IBM computers of that era had similar features.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] For example, the IBM 1401 system (1959) used a card reader to load a program from a punched card.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The 80 characters stored in the punched card were read into memory locations 001 to 080, then the computer would branch to memory location 001 to read its first stored instruction.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] This instruction was always the same: move the information in these first 80 memory locations to an assembly area where the information in punched cards 2, 3, 4, and so on, could be combined to form the stored program.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Once this information was moved to the assembly area, the machine would branch to an instruction in location 080 (read a card) and the next card would be read and its information processed.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Another example was the IBM 650 (1953), a decimal machine, which had a group of ten 10-position switches on its operator panel that were addressable as a memory word (address 8000) and could be executed as an instruction.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Thus, setting the switches to 7004000400 and pressing the appropriate button would read the first card in the card reader into memory (op code 70), starting at address 400 and then jump to 400 to begin executing the program on that card.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] IBM's competitors also offered single-button program load.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] A noteworthy variation of this is found on the Burroughs B1700, where there is neither a boot ROM nor a hardwired IPL operation.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Instead, after the system is reset, it reads and executes microinstructions sequentially from a cassette tape drive mounted on the front panel; this sets up a boot loader in RAM, which is then executed.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] However, since this makes few assumptions about the system it can equally well be used to load diagnostic (Maintenance Test Routine) tapes which display an intelligible code on the front panel even in cases of gross CPU failure.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] In the IBM System/360 and its successors, including the current z/Architecture machines, the boot process is known as *Initial Program Load* (IPL).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] IBM coined this term for the 7030 (Stretch), revived it for the design of the System/360, and continues to use it in those environments today.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] In the System/360 processors, an IPL is initiated by the computer operator by selecting the three hexadecimal digit device address (CUU; C=I/O Channel address, UU=Control unit and Device address) followed by pressing the *LOAD* button.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] On the high end System/360 models, most System/370 and some later systems, the functions of the switches and the LOAD button are simulated using selectable areas on the screen of a graphics console, often an IBM 2250-like device or an IBM 3270-like device.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] For example, on the System/370 Model 158, the keyboard sequence 0-7-X (zero, seven and X, in that order) results in an IPL from the device address that was keyed into the input area.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The Amdahl 470V/6 and related CPUs supported four hexadecimal digits on those CPUs that had the optional second channel unit installed, for a total of 32 channels.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Later, IBM would also support more than 16 channels.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The IPL function in the System/360 and its successors prior to IBM Z, and its compatibles, such as Amdahl's, reads 24 bytes from an operator-specified device into main storage starting at real address zero.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The second and third groups of eight bytes are treated as Channel Command Words (CCWs) to continue loading the startup program (the first CCW is always simulated by the CPU and consists of a Read IPL command, 02h, with command chaining and suppress incorrect length indication being enforced).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] When the I/O channel commands are complete, the first group of eight bytes is then loaded into the processor's Program Status Word (PSW) and the startup program begins execution at the location designated by that PSW.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] IBM introduced some evolutionary changes in the IPL process, changing some details for System/370 Extended Architecture (S/370-XA) and later, and adding a new type of IPL for z/Architecture.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Minicomputers, starting with the Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-5 and PDP-8 (1965) simplified design by using the CPU to assist input and output operations.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] This saved cost but made booting more complicated than pressing a single button.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Minicomputers typically had some way to *toggle in* short programs by manipulating an array of switches on the front panel.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Since the early minicomputers used magnetic-core memory, which did not lose its information when power was off, these bootstrap loaders would remain in place unless they were erased.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Erasure sometimes happened accidentally when a program bug caused a loop that overwrote all of memory.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Other minicomputers with such simple form of booting include Hewlett-Packard's HP 2100 series (mid-1960s), the original Data General Nova (1969), and DEC's PDP-4 (1962) and PDP-11 (1970).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] As the I/O operations needed to cause a read operation on a minicomputer I/O device were typically different for different device controllers, different bootstrap programs were needed for different devices.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] DEC later added, in 1971, an optional diode matrix read-only memory for the PDP-11 that stored a bootstrap program of up to 32 words (64 bytes).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] It consisted of a printed circuit card, the M792, that plugged into the Unibus and held a 32 by 16 array of semiconductor diodes.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] With all 512 diodes in place, the memory contained all "one" bits; the card was programmed by cutting off each diode whose bit was to be "zero".
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] DEC also sold versions of the card, the BM792-Yx series, pre-programmed for many standard input devices by simply omitting the unneeded diodes.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Following the older approach, the earlier PDP-1 has a hardware loader, such that an operator needs only push the *load* switch to instruct the paper tape reader to load a program directly into core memory.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The PDP-7, PDP-9, and PDP-15 successors to the PDP-4 have an added Read-In button to read a program in from paper tape and jump to it.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The Data General Supernova used front panel switches to cause the computer to automatically load instructions into memory from a device specified by the front panel's data switches, and then jump to loaded code.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] In a minicomputer with a paper tape reader, the first program to run in the boot process, the boot loader, would read into core memory either the second-stage boot loader (often called a *Binary Loader*) that could read paper tape with checksum or the operating system from an outside storage medium.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] A related example is based on a loader for a Nicolet Instrument Corporation minicomputer of the 1970s, using the paper tape reader-punch unit on a Teletype Model 33 ASR teleprinter.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The bytes of its second-stage loader are read from paper tape in reverse order.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The length of the second stage loader is such that the final byte overwrites location 7.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] After the instruction in location 6 executes, location 7 starts the second stage loader executing.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The second stage loader then waits for the much longer tape containing the operating system to be placed in the tape reader.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The difference between the boot loader and second stage loader is the addition of checking code to trap paper tape read errors, a frequent occurrence with relatively low-cost, "part-time-duty" hardware, such as the Teletype Model 33 ASR.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The earliest microcomputers, such as the Altair 8800 (released first in 1975) and an even earlier, similar machine (based on the Intel 8008 CPU) had no bootstrapping hardware as such.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] When powered up, the CPU would see memory that would contain random data.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The front panels of these machines carried toggle switches for entering addresses and data, one switch per bit of the computer memory word and address bus.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Simple additions to the hardware permitted one memory location at a time to be loaded from those switches to store bootstrap code.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Meanwhile, the CPU was kept from attempting to execute memory content.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Once correctly loaded, the CPU was enabled to execute the bootstrapping code.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] This process, similar to that used for several earlier minicomputers, was tedious and had to be error-free.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The introduction of integrated circuit read-only memory (ROM), with its many variants, including mask-programmed ROMs, programmable ROMs (PROM), erasable programmable ROMs (EPROM), and flash memory, reduced the physical size and cost of ROM.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] This allowed firmware boot programs to be included as part of the computer.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The Data General Nova 1200 (1970) and Nova 800 (1971) had a program load switch that, in combination with options that provided two ROM chips, loaded a program into main memory from those ROM chips and jumped to it.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Digital Equipment Corporation introduced the integrated-circuit-ROM-based BM873 (1974), M9301 (1977), M9312 (1978), REV11-A and REV11-C, MRV11-C, and MRV11-D ROM memories, all usable as bootstrap ROMs.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] An Italian telephone switching computer, called "Gruppi Speciali", patented in 1975 by Alberto Ciaramella, a researcher at CSELT, included an (external) ROM.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Gruppi Speciali was, starting from 1975, a fully single-button machine booting into the operating system from a ROM memory composed of semiconductors, not ferrite cores.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Although the ROM device was not natively embedded in the computer of Gruppi Speciali, due to the design of the machine, it also allowed the single-button ROM booting in machines not designed for that (therefore, this "bootstrap device" was architecture-independent), e.g., the PDP-11.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Storing the state of the machine after the switch-off was also in place, which was another critical feature in the telephone switching contest.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Some minicomputers and superminicomputers include a separate console processor that bootstraps the main processor.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The PDP-11/44 had an Intel 8085 as a console processor; the VAX-11/780, the first member of Digital's VAX line of 32-bit superminicomputers, had an LSI-11-based console processor, and the VAX-11/730 had an 8085-based console processor.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] These console processors could boot the main processor from various storage devices.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Some other superminicomputers, such as the VAX-11/750, implement console functions, including the first stage of booting, in CPU microcode.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] A system built using that microprocessor will have the permanent ROM occupying these special locations so that the system always begins operating without operator assistance.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] For example, Intel x86 processors always start by running the instructions beginning at F000:FFF0, while for the MOS 6502 processor, initialization begins by reading a two-byte vector address at $FFFD (MS byte) and $FFFC (LS byte) and jumping to that location to run the bootstrap code.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Apple Computer's first computer, the Apple 1, introduced in 1976, featured PROM chips that eliminated the need for a front panel for the boot process (as was the case with the Altair 8800) in a commercial computer.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Due to the expense of read-only memory at the time, the Apple II booted its disk operating systems using a series of very small incremental steps, each passing control onward to the next phase of the gradually more complex boot process.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Because so little of the disk operating system relied on ROM, the hardware was also extremely flexible and supported a wide range of customized disk copy protection mechanisms.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Some operating systems, most notably pre-1995 Macintosh systems from Apple, are so closely interwoven with their hardware that it is impossible to natively boot an operating system other than the standard one.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] This is the opposite extreme of the scenario using switches mentioned above; it is highly inflexible but relatively error-proof and foolproof as long as all hardware is working normally.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] A common solution in such situations is to design a boot loader that works as a program belonging to the standard OS that hijacks the system and loads the alternative OS.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] This technique was used by Apple for its A/UX Unix implementation and copied by various freeware operating systems and BeOS Personal Edition 5.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Some machines, like the Atari ST microcomputer, were "instant-on", with the operating system executing from a ROM.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Retrieval of the OS from secondary or tertiary store was thus eliminated as one of the characteristic operations for bootstrapping.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] To allow system customizations, accessories, and other support software to be loaded automatically, the Atari's floppy drive was read for additional components during the boot process.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] There was a timeout delay that provided time to manually insert a floppy as the system searched for the extra components.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] This could be avoided by inserting a blank disk.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The IBM Personal Computer included ROM-based firmware called the BIOS; one of the functions of that firmware was to perform a power-on self test when the machine was powered up, and then to read software from a boot device and execute it.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Firmware compatible with the BIOS on the IBM Personal Computer is used in IBM PC compatible computers.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The UEFI was developed by Intel, originally for Itanium-based machines, and later also used as an alternative to the BIOS in x86-based machines, including Apple Macs using Intel processors.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Unix workstations originally had vendor-specific ROM-based firmware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Sun Microsystems later developed OpenBoot, later known as Open Firmware, which incorporated a Forth interpreter, with much of the firmware being written in Forth.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] It was standardized by the IEEE as IEEE standard 1275-1994; firmware that implements that standard was used in PowerPC-based Macs and some other PowerPC-based machines, as well as Sun's own SPARC-based computers.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The Advanced RISC Computing specification defined another firmware standard, which was implemented on some MIPS-based and Alpha-based machines and the SGI Visual Workstation x86-based workstations.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] When a computer is turned off, its software‍—‌including operating systems, application code, and data‍—‌remains stored on non-volatile memory.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] When the computer is powered on, it typically does not have an operating system or its loader in random-access memory (RAM).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The small program that starts this sequence is known as a *bootstrap loader*, *bootstrap* or *boot loader*.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Often, multiple-stage boot loaders are used, during which several programs of increasing complexity load one after the other in a process of chain loading.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Some earlier computer systems, upon receiving a boot signal from a human operator or a peripheral device, may load a very small number of fixed instructions into memory at a specific location, initialize at least one CPU, and then point the CPU to the instructions and start their execution.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] These instructions typically start an input operation from some peripheral device (which may be switch-selectable by the operator).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Smaller computers often use less flexible but more automatic boot loader mechanisms to ensure that the computer starts quickly and with a predetermined software configuration.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] In many desktop computers, for example, the bootstrapping process begins with the CPU executing software contained in ROM (for example, the BIOS of an IBM PC) at a predefined address (some CPUs, including the Intel x86 series are designed to execute this software after reset without outside help).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] This software contains rudimentary functionality to search for devices eligible to participate in booting, and load a small program from a special section (most commonly the boot sector) of the most promising device, typically starting at a fixed entry point such as the start of the sector.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] On systems with those constraints, the first program loaded into RAM may not be sufficiently large to load the operating system and, instead, must load another, larger program.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The first program loaded into RAM is called a first-stage boot loader, and the program it loads is called a second-stage boot loader.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] On many embedded CPUs, the CPU built-in boot ROM, sometimes called the zero-stage boot loader, can find and load first-stage boot loaders.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Examples of first-stage (hardware initialization stage) boot loaders include BIOS, UEFI, coreboot, Libreboot and Das U-Boot.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] On the IBM PC, the boot loader in the Master Boot Record (MBR) and the Partition Boot Record (PBR) was coded to require at least 32 KB (later expanded to 64 KB) of system memory and only use instructions supported by the original 8088/8086 processors.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The second-stage boot loader does not need drivers for its own operation, but may instead use generic storage access methods provided by system firmware such as the BIOS, UEFI or Open Firmware, though typically with restricted hardware functionality and lower performance.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Many boot loaders (like GNU GRUB, rEFInd, Windows's BOOTMGR, Syslinux, and Windows NT/2000/XP's NTLDR) can be configured to give the user multiple booting choices.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Some boot loaders can also load other boot loaders; for example, GRUB loads BOOTMGR instead of loading Windows directly.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Usually, a default choice is preselected with a time delay during which a user can press a key to change the choice; after this delay, the default choice is automatically run so normal booting can occur without interaction.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The boot process can be considered complete when the computer is ready to interact with the user, or the operating system is capable of running system programs or application programs.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Some boot loaders, such as Das U-Boot and iBoot, include both first- and second-stage boot functions.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Many embedded systems must boot immediately.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] For example, waiting a minute for a digital television or a GPS navigation device to start is generally unacceptable.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Therefore, such devices have software systems in ROM or flash memory so the device can begin functioning immediately; little or no loading is necessary, because the loading can be precomputed and stored on the ROM when the device is made.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Large and complex systems may have boot procedures that proceed in multiple phases until finally the operating system and other programs are loaded and ready to execute.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Because operating systems are designed as if they never start or stop, a boot loader might load the operating system, configure itself as a mere process within that system, and then irrevocably transfer control to the operating system.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The boot loader then terminates normally as any other process would.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Most computers are also capable of booting over a computer network.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] In this scenario, the operating system is stored on the disk of a server, and certain parts of it are transferred to the client using a simple protocol such as the Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] After these parts have been transferred, the operating system takes over control of the booting process.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] As with the second-stage boot loader, network booting begins by using generic network access methods provided by the network interface's boot ROM, which typically contains a Preboot Execution Environment (PXE) image.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] No drivers are required, but the system functionality is limited until the operating system kernel and drivers are transferred and started.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] As a result, once the ROM-based booting has completed it is entirely possible to network boot into an operating system that itself does not have the ability to use the network interface.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The boot device is the storage device from which the operating system is loaded.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Older, less common BIOS-bootable devices include floppy disk drives, Zip drives, and LS-120 drives.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] IBM-compatible PCs are examples that use horizontal integrated hardware and UEFI/BIOS firmware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Typically, the system firmware (UEFI or BIOS) will allow the user to configure a *boot order*.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] If the boot order is set to "first, the DVD drive; second, the hard disk drive", then the firmware will try to boot from the DVD drive, and if this fails (e.g., because there is no DVD in the drive), it will try to boot from the local hard disk drive.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] For example, on a PC with Windows installed on the hard drive, the user could set the boot order to the one given above, and then insert a Linux Live CD in order to try out Linux without having to install an operating system onto the hard drive.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] This is an example of dual booting, in which the user chooses which operating system to start after the computer has performed its power-on self-test (POST).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Several devices are available that enable the user to *quick-boot* into what is usually a variant of Linux for various simple tasks such as Internet access; examples are Splashtop and Latitude ON.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] This memory location typically contains a jump instruction that transfers execution to the location of the firmware (UEFI or BIOS) start-up program.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] This program runs a power-on self-test (POST) to check and initialize required devices such as main memory (DRAM), the PCI bus and the PCI devices (including running embedded option ROMs).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] One of the most involved steps is setting up DRAM over SPD, further complicated by the fact that, at this point, memory is very limited.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] After initializing required hardware, the firmware (UEFI or BIOS) goes through a pre-configured list of non-volatile storage devices ("boot device sequence") until it finds one that is bootable.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Once the BIOS has found a bootable device it loads the boot sector to linear address 7C00h (usually segment:offset 0000h:7C00h, but some BIOSes erroneously use 07C0h:0000h) and transfers execution to the boot code.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] In the case of a hard disk, this is referred to as the Master Boot Record (MBR).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The conventional MBR code checks the MBR's partition table for a partition set as *bootable* (the one with *active* flag set).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] If an active partition is found, the MBR code loads the boot sector code from that partition, known as Volume Boot Record (VBR), and executes it.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The MBR boot code is often operating-system specific.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The boot sector code is the first-stage boot loader.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The boot loader was then able to load the first three sectors of the file into memory, which happened to contain another embedded boot loader able to load the remainder of the file into memory.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] When Microsoft added LBA and FAT32 support, they even switched to a boot loader reaching over *two* physical sectors and using 386 instructions for size reasons.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] At the same time, other vendors managed to squeeze much more functionality into a single boot sector without relaxing the original constraints on only minimal available memory (32 KB) and processor support (8088/8086).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] For example, DR-DOS boot sectors are able to locate the boot file in the FAT12, FAT16 and FAT32 file system, and load it into memory as a whole via CHS or LBA, even if the file is not stored in a fixed location and in consecutive sectors.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The VBR is often OS-specific; however, its main function is to load and execute the operating system boot loader file (such as `bootmgr` or `ntldr`), which is the second-stage boot loader, from an active partition.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Then the boot loader loads the OS kernel from the storage device.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] If there is no active partition, or the active partition's boot sector is invalid, the MBR may load a secondary boot loader which will select a partition (often via user input) and load its boot sector, which usually loads the corresponding operating system kernel.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] In some cases, the MBR may also attempt to load secondary boot loaders before trying to boot the active partition.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] If all else fails, it should issue an INT 18h BIOS interrupt call (followed by an INT 19h just in case INT 18h would return) in order to give back control to the BIOS, which would then attempt to boot off other devices, attempt a remote boot via network.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Many modern systems (Intel Macs and newer PCs) use UEFI.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Unlike BIOS, UEFI (not **Legacy boot** via CSM) does not rely on boot sectors, UEFI system loads the boot loader (**EFI application** file in USB disk or in the EFI System Partition) directly, and the OS kernel is loaded by the boot loader.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] It is difficult to hardwire all the required logic for handling such devices, so an integrated boot ROM is used instead in such scenarios.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Also, a boot ROM may be able to load a boot loader or diagnostic program via serial interfaces like UART, SPI, USB and so on.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] This feature is often used for system recovery purposes, or it could also be used for initial non-volatile memory programming when there is no software available in the non-volatile memory yet.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Many modern microcontrollers (e.g., flash memory controller on USB flash drives) have firmware ROM integrated directly into their silicon.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Some embedded system designs may also include an intermediary boot sequence step.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] For example, Das U-Boot may be split into two stages: the platform would load a small SPL (Secondary Program Loader), which is a stripped-down version of U-Boot, and the SPL would do some initial hardware configuration (e.g.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] DRAM initialization using CPU cache as RAM) and load the larger, fully featured version of U-Boot.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Such embedded systems may used highly customized and vertical integrated hardware and software, and their boot programs may be simpler.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Some CPUs and SoCs may not use CPU cache as RAM on boot process, they use an integrated boot processor to do some hardware configuration to reduce cost.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] It is also possible to take control of a system by using a hardware debug interface such as JTAG.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Such an interface may be used to write the boot loader program into bootable non-volatile memory (e.g. flash) by instructing the processor core to perform the necessary actions to program non-volatile memory.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Alternatively, the debug interface may be used to upload some diagnostic or boot code into RAM, and then to start the processor core and instruct it to execute the uploaded code.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] This allows, for example, the recovery of embedded systems where no software remains on any supported boot device, and where the processor does not have any integrated boot ROM.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] JTAG is a standard and popular interface; many CPUs, microcontrollers and other devices are manufactured with JTAG interfaces (as of 2009).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Some microcontrollers provide special hardware interfaces that cannot be used to take arbitrary control of a system or directly run code, but instead allow the insertion of boot code into bootable non-volatile memory (like flash memory) via simple protocols.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Then, at the manufacturing phase, such interfaces are used to inject boot code (and possibly other code) into non-volatile memory.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] After system reset, the microcontroller begins to execute code programmed into its non-volatile memory, just like usual processors use ROMs for booting.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Most notably, this technique is used by Atmel AVR microcontrollers, and by others as well.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] In many cases, such interfaces are implemented by hardwired logic.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] In other cases, such interfaces could be created by software running in integrated on-chip boot ROM from GPIO pins.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Most DSPs have a serial mode boot and a parallel mode boot, such as the host port interface (HPI boot).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] In the case of DSPs, there is often a second microprocessor or microcontroller present in the system design, and this is responsible for overall system behavior, interrupt handling, dealing with external events, user interface, etc., while the DSP is dedicated to signal processing tasks only.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] In such systems, the DSP could be booted by another processor, which is sometimes referred as the *host processor* (giving name to a Host Port).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Such a processor is also sometimes referred to as the *master*, since it usually boots first from its own memories and then controls overall system behavior, including booting of the DSP, and then further controls the DSP's behavior.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The DSP often lacks its own boot memories and relies on the host processor to supply the required code instead.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The most notable systems with such a design are cell phones, modems, audio and video players and so on, where a DSP and a CPU/microcontroller coexist.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Many FPGA chips load their configuration from an external configuration ROM, typically a serial EEPROM, on power-up.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Various measures have been implemented that enhance the security of the booting process.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Some of them are made mandatory, others can be disabled or enabled by the end user.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Traditionally, booting did not involve the use of cryptography.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The security can be bypassed by unlocking the boot loader, which might or might not be approved by the manufacturer.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Modern boot loaders make use of concurrency, meaning they can run multiple processor cores and threads at the same time, which adds extra layers of complexity to secure booting.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Matthew Garrett argued that booting security serves a legitimate goal, but in doing so chooses defaults that are hostile to users.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] The system might exhibit its erroneous state in, for example, an explicit bootloop or a blue screen of death, before recovery is indicated.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Detection of an erroneous state may require a distributed event store and stream-processing platform for real-time operation of a distributed system.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] An erroneous state can trigger bootloops; this state can be caused by misconfiguration from previously known-good operations.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Recovery attempts from that erroneous state then enter a reboot, in an attempt to return to a known-good state.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] In Windows OS operations, for example, the recovery procedure was to reboot three times, the reboots needed to return to a usable menu.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] Recovery might be specified via Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML), which can also implement Single sign-on (SSO) for some applications; in the zero trust security model, identification, authorization, and authentication are separable concerns in an SSO session.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/booting] When recovery of a site is indicated (viz., a blue screen of death is displayed on an airport terminal screen) personal site visits might be required to remediate the situation.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Code signing can provide several valuable features.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] The most common use of code signing is to provide security when deploying; in some programming languages, it can also be used to help prevent namespace conflicts.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Almost every code signing implementation will provide some sort of digital signature mechanism to verify the identity of the author or build system, and a checksum to verify that the object has not been modified.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] It can also be used to provide versioning information about an object or to store other metadata about an object.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] The efficacy of code signing as an authentication mechanism for software depends on the security of underpinning signing keys.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] As with other public key infrastructure (PKI) technologies, the integrity of the system relies on publishers securing their private keys against unauthorized access.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Keys stored in software on general-purpose computers are susceptible to compromise.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Therefore, it is more secure, and best practice, to store keys in secure, tamper-proof, cryptographic hardware devices known as hardware security modules or HSMs.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Many code signing implementations will provide a way to sign the code using a system involving a pair of keys, one public and one private, similar to the process employed by TLS or SSH.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] For example, in the case of .NET, the developer uses a private key to sign their libraries or executables each time they build.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] This key will be unique to a developer or group or sometimes per application or object.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] The developer can either generate this key on their own or obtain one from a trusted certificate authority (CA).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Code signing is particularly valuable in distributed environments, where the source of a given piece of code may not be immediately evident - for example Java applets, ActiveX controls and other active web and browser scripting code.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Another important usage is to safely provide updates and patches to existing software.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Windows, Mac OS X, and most Linux distributions provide updates using code signing to ensure that it is not possible for others to maliciously distribute code via the patch system.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] It allows the receiving operating system to verify that the update is legitimate, even if the update was delivered by third parties or physical media (disks).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Code signing is used on Windows and Mac OS X to authenticate software on first run, ensuring that the software has not been maliciously tampered with by a third-party distributor or download site.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Debian-based Linux distributions (among others) validate downloaded packages using public key cryptography.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] The public key used to authenticate the code signature should be traceable back to a trusted root authority CA, preferably using a secure public key infrastructure (PKI).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] This does not ensure that the code itself can be trusted, only that it comes from the stated source (or more explicitly, from a particular private key).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] A CA provides a root trust level and is able to assign trust to others by proxy.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] If a user trusts a CA, then the user can presumably trust the legitimacy of code that is signed with a key generated by that CA or one of its proxies.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Many operating systems and frameworks contain built-in trust for one or more certification authorities.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] It is also commonplace for large organizations to implement a private CA, internal to the organization, which provides the same features as public CAs, but it is only trusted within the organization.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Extended validation (EV) code signing certificates are subject to additional validation and technical requirements.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] These guidelines are based on the CA/B Forum's Baseline Requirements and Extended Validation Guidelines.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Certain applications, such as signing Windows 10 kernel-mode drivers, require an EV code signing certificate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] This is an example of a decoded EV code signing certificate used by SSL.com to sign software.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] `SSL.com EV Code Signing Intermediate CA RSA R3` is shown as the Issuer's commonName, identifying this as an EV code signing certificate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] The certificate's `Subject` field describes SSL Corp as an organization.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] `Code Signing` is shown as the sole X509v3 Extended Key Usage.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] The other model is the trust on first use model, in which developers can choose to provide their own self-generated key.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] In this scenario, the user would normally have to obtain the public key in some fashion directly from the developer to verify the object is from them for the first time.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Many code signing systems will store the public key inside the signature.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Some software frameworks and OSs that check the code's signature before executing will allow you to choose to trust that developer from that point on after the first run.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] An application developer can provide a similar system by including the public keys with the installer.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] The key can then be used to ensure that any subsequent objects that need to run, such as upgrades, plugins, or another application, are all verified as coming from that same developer.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Time-stamping was designed to circumvent the trust warning that will appear in the case of an expired certificate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] In effect, time-stamping extends the code trust beyond the validity period of a certificate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] In the event that a certificate has to be revoked due to a compromise, a specific date and time of the compromising event will become part of the revocation record.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] In this case, time-stamping helps establish whether the code was signed before or after the certificate was compromised.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Developers need to sign their iOS and tvOS apps before running them on any real device and before uploading them to the App Store.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] This is needed to prove that the developer owns a valid Apple Developer ID.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] An application needs a valid profile or certificate so that it can run on the devices.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Like any security measure, code signing can be defeated.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Users can be tricked into running unsigned code, or even into running code that refuses to validate, and the system only remains secure as long as the private key remains private.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] It is also important to note that code signing does not protect the end user from any malicious activity or unintentional software bugs by the software author — it merely ensures that the software has not been modified by anyone other than the author.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Sometimes, sandbox systems do not accept certificates, because of a false time-stamp or because of an excess usage of RAM.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Microsoft implements a form of code signing (based on Authenticode) provided for Microsoft tested drivers.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Since drivers run in the kernel, they can destabilize the system or open the system to security holes.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] For this reason, Microsoft tests drivers submitted to its WHQL program.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] After the driver has passed, Microsoft signs that version of the driver as being safe.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] On 32-bit systems only, installing drivers that are not validated with Microsoft is possible after agreeing to allow the installation at a prompt warning the user that the code is unsigned.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] For .NET (managed) code, there is an additional mechanism called Strong Name Signing that uses Public/Private keys and SHA-1 hash as opposed to certificates.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] However, Microsoft discourages reliance on Strong Name Signing as a replacement for Authenticode.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] The CAs subsequently issued announcements on compliance with the decision.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] In the context of consumer devices such as games consoles, the term "unsigned code" is often used to refer to an application which has not been signed with the cryptographic key normally required for software to be accepted and executed.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] Most console games have to be signed with a secret key designed by the console maker or the game will not load on the console (both to enforce Vendor lock-in and combat software piracy).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] There are several methods to get unsigned code to execute which include software exploits, the use of a modchip, a technique known as the swap trick or running a softmod.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] It may not initially seem obvious why simply copying a signed application onto another DVD does not allow it to boot.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] On the Xbox, the reason for this is that the Xbox executable file (XBE) contains a media-type flag, which specifies the type of media that the XBE is bootable from.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] On nearly all Xbox software, this is set such that the executable will only boot from factory-produced discs, so simply copying the executable to burnable media is enough to stop the execution of the software.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/code-signing] However, since the executable is signed, simply changing the value of the flag is not possible as this alters the signature of the executable, causing it to fail validation when checked.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] In computing, **firmware** (**FW**) is software that provides low-level control of computer hardware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] For a relatively simple device, firmware may perform all control, monitoring and data manipulation functionality.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] For a more complex device, firmware may provide only relatively low-level control as well as hardware abstraction to higher-level software such as an operating system.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Firmware is found in a wide range of computing devices, including personal computers, smartphones, home appliances, vehicles, computer peripherals and in many of the integrated circuits inside each of these larger systems.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Firmware is stored in non-volatile memory – either read-only memory (ROM) or programmable memory such as EPROM, EEPROM, or flash.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Changing a device's firmware stored in ROM requires physically replacing the memory chip or the device itself.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Programmable firmware memory can be reprogrammed via a procedure sometimes called *flashing*.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Common reasons for changing firmware include fixing bugs and adding features.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Ascher Opler used the term *firmware* in a 1967 *Datamation* article, as an intermediary term between *hardware* and *software*.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Opler projected that fourth-generation computer systems would have a writable control store (a small specialized high-speed memory) into which microcode firmware would be loaded.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Many software functions would be moved to microcode, and instruction sets could be customized, with different firmware loaded for different instruction sets.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] As computers began to increase in complexity, it became clear that various programs needed to first be initiated and run to provide a consistent environment necessary for running more complex programs at the user's discretion.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] This required programming the computer to run those programs automatically.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Furthermore, as companies, universities, and marketers wanted to sell computers to laypeople with little technical knowledge, greater automation became necessary to allow a layperson to easily run programs for practical purposes.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] This gave rise to a kind of software that a user would not consciously run, and it led to software that a lay user would not even know about.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] As originally used, firmware contrasted with hardware (the CPU itself) and software (normal instructions executing on a CPU).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] It was not composed of CPU machine instructions, but of lower-level microcode involved in the implementation of machine instructions.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] It existed on the boundary between hardware and software; thus the name *firmware*.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] In some respects, the various firmware components are as important as the operating system in a working computer.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] However, unlike most modern operating systems, firmware rarely has a well-evolved automatic mechanism of updating itself to fix any functionality issues detected after shipping the unit.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] A computer's firmware may be manually updated by a user via a small utility program.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] In contrast, firmware in mass storage devices (hard-disk drives, optical disc drives, flash memory storage e.g., solid state drive) is less frequently updated, even when flash memory (rather than ROM, EEPROM) storage is used for the firmware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Most computer peripherals are themselves special-purpose computers.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Devices such as printers, scanners, webcams, and USB flash drives have internally-stored firmware; some devices may also permit field upgrading of their firmware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] For modern, simpler devices, such as USB keyboards, USB mouses and USB sound cards, the trend is to store the firmware in on-chip memory in the device's microcontroller, as opposed to storing it in a separate EEPROM chip.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Consumer products like digital cameras and portable music players support firmware upgrades.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] In digital cameras, firmware upgrades address bugs in the operation, along with adding new functions to the camera's operation.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Some companies use firmware updates to add new playable file formats (codecs).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Other features that may change with firmware updates include the user interface or even the battery life.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Since 1996, most automobiles have employed an on-board computer and various sensors to detect mechanical problems.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] As of 2010, modern vehicles also employ computer-controlled anti-lock braking systems (ABS) and computer-operated transmission control units (TCUs).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] The driver can also get in-dash information while driving in this manner, such as real-time fuel economy and tire pressure readings.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Local dealers can update most vehicle firmware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Sometimes, third parties develop an unofficial new or modified ("aftermarket") version of firmware to provide new features or to unlock hidden functionality; this is referred to as custom firmware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] An example is Rockbox as a firmware replacement for portable media players.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] There are many homebrew projects for various devices, which often unlock general-purpose computing functionality in previously limited devices (e.g., running Doom on iPods).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Firmware hacks usually take advantage of the firmware update facility on many devices to install or run themselves.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Some, however, must resort to exploits to run, because the manufacturer has attempted to lock the hardware to stop it from running unlicensed code.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Although the Kaspersky Lab report did not explicitly claim that this group is part of the United States National Security Agency (NSA), evidence obtained from the code of various Equation Group software suggests that they are part of the NSA.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Researchers from the Kaspersky Lab categorized the undertakings by Equation Group as the most advanced hacking operation ever uncovered, also documenting around 500 infections caused by the Equation Group in at least 42 countries.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Mark Shuttleworth, the founder of the company Canonical, which created the Ubuntu Linux distribution, has described proprietary firmware as a security risk, saying that "firmware on your device is the NSA's best friend" and calling firmware "a trojan horse of monumental proportions".
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] As a potential solution to this problem, he has called for declarative firmware, which would describe "hardware linkage and dependencies" and "should not include executable code".
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Firmware should be open-source so that the code can be checked and verified.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Custom firmware hacks have also focused on injecting malware into devices such as smartphones or USB devices.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] One such smartphone injection was demonstrated on the Symbian OS at MalCon, a hacker convention.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] A USB device firmware hack called BadUSB was presented at the Black Hat USA 2014 conference, demonstrating how a USB flash drive microcontroller can be reprogrammed to spoof various other device types to take control of a computer, exfiltrate data, or spy on the user.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/firmware] Other security researchers have worked further on how to exploit the principles behind BadUSB, releasing at the same time the source code of hacking tools that can be used to modify the behavior of different USB devices.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] In cryptography, a **public-key certificate**, also known as a **digital certificate** or **identity certificate**, is an electronic document used to prove the valid attribution of a public key to the identity of its holder.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The certificate includes the public key and information about it, information about the identity of its owner (called the subject), and the digital signature of an entity that has verified the certificate's contents (called the issuer).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] If the party examining the certificate trusts the issuer and finds the signature to be a valid signature of that issuer, then it can use the included public key to interact securely with the certificate's subject.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] In email encryption, code signing, and e-signature systems, a certificate's subject is typically a person or organization.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] However, in Transport Layer Security (TLS) a certificate's subject is typically a computer or other device, though TLS certificates may identify organizations or individuals in addition to their core role in identifying devices.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] TLS, sometimes called by its older name Secure Sockets Layer (SSL), is notable for being a part of HTTPS, a protocol for securely browsing the web.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] In a typical public-key infrastructure (PKI) scheme, the certificate issuer is a certificate authority (CA), usually a company that charges customers a fee to issue certificates for them.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] By contrast, in a web of trust scheme, individuals sign each other's keys directly, in a format that performs a similar function to a public-key certificate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] A public-key certificate is typically requested from a PKI using a CSR, which needs to be transferred using a secure certificate enrollment protocol such as CMP, EST, or ACME.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The parties involved in the enrollment process must verify the authenticity, integrity, and authorization of the CSR, for which the certificate issuer bears the main responsibility.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] In case of key compromise or other situations that may lead to unauthorized use, a certificate may need to be revoked.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The general format for public-key and attribute certificates is defined by X.509.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] For public-key certificates, the format has been profiled by the IETF for Internet-related use cases, such as Public-Key Infrastructure (X.509).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] A digital certificate system provides a chain of trust, meaning most certificates can be validated against parent certificates.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The chain starts with a **root certificate**, which serves as a trust anchor (a.k.a. root of trust).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] This certificate is self-signed (see below) and has no parent.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The issuing certificate authority uses other methods to safeguard and validate this certificate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] An **intermediate certificate** has a purpose similar to that of the root certificate – its only use is to sign other certificates.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] However, an intermediate certificate is not self-signed.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] A root certificate or another intermediate certificate needs to sign it.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] An **end-entity certificate**, or **leaf certificate**, is any certificate that cannot sign other certificates.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] For instance, TLS/SSL server and client certificates, email certificates, code signing certificates, and qualified certificates are all end-entity certificates.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol – as well as its outdated predecessor, the Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) protocol – ensures that the communication between a client computer and a server is secure.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The protocol requires the server to present a digital certificate, proving that it is the intended destination.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] A trusted certificate authority has signed the certificate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The *Subject* field of the certificate must identify the primary hostname of the server as the *Common Name*.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] This means that the name listed in the certificate should exactly match the domain name users connect to (for example, `www.example.com`), ensuring that the certificate is valid for that specific hostname.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The hostname must be publicly accessible, not using private addresses or reserved domains.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] A certificate may be valid for multiple hostnames (e.g., a domain and its subdomains).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Such certificates are commonly called *Subject Alternative Name (SAN) certificates* or *Unified Communications Certificates (UCC)*.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] These certificates contain the Subject Alternative Name field, though many CAs also put them into the *Subject Common Name* field for backward compatibility.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] If some of the hostnames contain an asterisk (*), a certificate may also be called a wildcard certificate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Once the certification path validation is successful, the client can establish an encrypted connection with the server.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Internet-facing servers, such as public Web servers, must obtain their certificates from a trusted, public certificate authority (CA).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Client certificates authenticate the client connecting to a TLS service, for instance to provide access control.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Because most services provide access to individuals, rather than devices, most client certificates contain an email address or personal name rather than a hostname.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] In addition, the certificate authority that issues the client certificate is usually the service provider to which client connects because it is the provider that needs to perform authentication.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] While most web browsers support client certificates, the most common form of authentication on the Internet is a username and password pair.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Client certificates are more common in virtual private networks (VPN) and Remote Desktop Services, where they authenticate devices.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] In accordance with the S/MIME protocol, email certificates can both establish the message integrity and encrypt messages.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] To establish encrypted email communication, the communicating parties must have their digital certificates in advance.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Each must send the other one digitally signed email and opt to import the sender's certificate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Some publicly trusted certificate authorities provide email certificates, but more commonly S/MIME is used when communicating within a given organization, and that organization runs its own CA, which is trusted by participants in that email system.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] A self-signed certificate is a certificate with a subject that matches its issuer, and a signature that can be verified by its own public key.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Although this type of certificate is worthless for establishing remote trust between unacquainted parties, it has full trust value when the issuer and the sole user are the same entity.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] As discussed above (in § Chain of trust), a root certificate is a self-signed certificate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The certificate authority, which is the sole user of the certificate, uses other means to validate and safeguard it.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Another example is the Encrypting File System on Microsoft Windows, which issues a self-signed certificate on behalf of the encrypting user, and uses it to transparently decrypt data on the fly.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Subject Alternative Name (SAN) certificates are an extension to X.509 that allows various values to be associated with a security certificate using a `subjectAltName` field.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] These values are called *Subject Alternative Names* (SANs).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] As of May 2000, Subject Alternative Names are the preferred method of adding DNS names to certificates.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The previous method of putting DNS names in the `commonName` field is now deprecated.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Google Chrome version 58 (March 2017) removed support for checking the `commonName` field at all, instead only looking at the SANs.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] As shown in the picture of Wikimedia's section on the right, the SAN field can contain wildcards.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Not all vendors support or endorse mixing wildcards into SAN certificates.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] A public-key certificate which uses an asterisk `*` (the *wildcard*) in the domain name portion of it subject is called a Wildcard certificate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Through the use of `*`, a single certificate may be used for multiple sub-domains.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] It is commonly used for transport layer security in computer networking.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Instead of getting separate certificates for subdomains, you can use a single certificate for all main domains and subdomains and reduce cost.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Note possible exceptions by CAs, for example wildcard-plus cert by DigiCert contains an automatic "Plus" property for the naked domain `example.com`.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Only a single level of subdomain matching is supported.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] It is not possible to get a wildcard for an Extended Validation Certificate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] A workaround could be to add every virtual host name in the Subject Alternative Name (SAN) extension, the major problem being that the certificate needs to be reissued whenever a new virtual server is added.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Wildcards can be added as domains in multi-domain certificates or Unified Communications Certificates (UCC).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] In addition, wildcards themselves can have `subjectAltName` extensions, including other wildcards.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] For example, the wildcard certificate `*.wikipedia.org` has `*.m.wikimedia.org` as a Subject Alternative Name.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Thus it secures `www.wikipedia.org` as well as the completely different website name `meta.m.wikimedia.org`.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] RFC 6125 argues against wildcard certificates on security grounds, in particular "partial wildcards".
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The wildcard applies only to one level of the domain name.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] However, use of "partial-wildcard" certs is not recommended.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] As of 2011, partial wildcard support is optional, and is explicitly disallowed in SubjectAltName headers that are required for multi-name certificates.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] All major browsers have deliberately **removed** support for partial-wildcard certificates; they will result in a "SSL_ERROR_BAD_CERT_DOMAIN" error.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Similarly, it is typical for standard libraries in programming languages to not support "partial-wildcard" certificates.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] For example, any "partial-wildcard" certificate will not work with the latest versions of both Python and Go.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] A cert with multiple wildcards in a name is not allowed.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] A cert with `*` plus a top-level domain is not allowed.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] International domain names encoded in ASCII (A-label) are labels that are ASCII-encoded and begin with `xn--`.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] URLs with international labels cannot contain wildcards.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] These are some of the most common fields in certificates.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Most certificates contain a number of fields not listed here.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Note that in terms of a certificate's X.509 representation, a certificate is not "flat" but contains these fields nested in various structures within the certificate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] This is an example of a decoded SSL/TLS certificate retrieved from SSL.com's website.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The issuer's common name (CN) is shown as `SSL.com EV SSL Intermediate CA RSA R3`, identifying this as an Extended Validation (EV) certificate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Validated information about the website's owner (SSL Corp) is located in the `Subject` field.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The `X509v3 Subject Alternative Name` field contains a list of domain names covered by the certificate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The `X509v3 Extended Key Usage` and `X509v3 Key Usage` fields show all appropriate uses.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] In the European Union, (advanced) electronic signatures on legal documents are commonly performed using digital signatures with accompanying identity certificates.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] However, only qualified electronic signatures (which require using a qualified trust service provider and signature creation device) are given the same power as a physical signature.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] In the X.509 trust model, a certificate authority (CA) is responsible for signing certificates.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] These certificates act as an introduction between two parties, which means that a CA acts as a trusted third party.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] A CA processes requests from people or organizations requesting certificates (called subscribers), verifies the information, and potentially signs an end-entity certificate based on that information.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] To perform this role effectively, a CA needs to have one or more broadly trusted root certificates or intermediate certificates and the corresponding private keys.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] CAs may achieve this broad trust by having their root certificates included in popular software, or by obtaining a cross-signature from another CA delegating trust.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Other CAs are trusted within a relatively small community, like a business, and are distributed by other mechanisms like Windows Group Policy.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Certificate authorities are also responsible for maintaining up-to-date revocation information about certificates they have issued, indicating whether certificates are still valid.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] They provide this information through Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) and/or Certificate Revocation Lists (CRLs).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Some of the larger certificate authorities in the market include IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Some major software contain a list of certificate authorities that are trusted by default.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] This makes it easier for end-users to validate certificates, and easier for people or organizations that request certificates to know which certificate authorities can issue a certificate that will be broadly trusted.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] This is particularly important in HTTPS, where a web site operator generally wants to get a certificate that is trusted by nearly all potential visitors to their web site.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The policies and processes a provider uses to decide which certificate authorities their software should trust are called root programs.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Browsers other than Firefox generally use the operating system's facilities to decide which certificate authorities are trusted.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] So, for instance, Chrome on Windows trusts the certificate authorities included in the Microsoft Root Program, while on macOS or iOS, Chrome trusts the certificate authorities in the Apple Root Program.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Edge and Safari use their respective operating system trust stores as well, but each is only available on a single OS.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Firefox uses the Mozilla Root Program trust store on all platforms.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The Mozilla Root Program is operated publicly, and its certificate list is part of the open source Firefox web browser, so it is broadly used outside Firefox.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] For instance, while there is no common Linux Root Program, many Linux distributions, like Debian, include a package that periodically copies the contents of the Firefox trust list, which is then used by applications.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Root programs generally provide a set of valid purposes with the certificates they include.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] For instance, some CAs may be considered trusted for issuing TLS server certificates, but not for code signing certificates.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] This is indicated with a set of trust bits in a root certificate storage system.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] A certificate may be revoked before it expires, which signals that it is no longer valid.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Without revocation, an attacker would be able to exploit such a compromised or misissued certificate until expiry.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Hence, revocation is an important part of a public key infrastructure.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Revocation is performed by the issuing certificate authority, which produces a cryptographically authenticated statement of revocation.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] For distributing revocation information to clients, timeliness of the discovery of revocation (and hence the window for an attacker to exploit a compromised certificate) trades off against resource usage in querying revocation statuses and privacy concerns.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] If revocation information is unavailable (either due to accident or an attack), clients must decide whether to *fail-hard* and treat a certificate as if it is revoked (and so degrade availability) or to *fail-soft* and treat it as unrevoked (and allow attackers to sidestep revocation).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Due to the cost of revocation checks and the availability impact from potentially-unreliable remote services, Web browsers limit the revocation checks they will perform, and will fail-soft where they do.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Certificate revocation lists are too bandwidth-costly for routine use, and the Online Certificate Status Protocol presents connection latency and privacy issues.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Other schemes have been proposed but have not yet been successfully deployed to enable fail-hard checking.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The most common use of certificates is for HTTPS-based web sites.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] A web browser validates that an HTTPS web server is authentic, so that the user can feel secure that his/her interaction with the web site has no eavesdroppers and that the web site is who it claims to be.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] This security is important for electronic commerce.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] In practice, a web site operator obtains a certificate by applying to a certificate authority with a certificate signing request.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The certificate request is an electronic document that contains the web site name, company information and the public key.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The certificate provider signs the request, thus producing a public certificate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] During web browsing, this public certificate is served to any web browser that connects to the web site and proves to the web browser that the provider believes it has issued a certificate to the owner of the web site.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Further, the relationship between the purchaser of the certificate, the operator of the web site, and the generator of the web site content may be tenuous and is not guaranteed.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] At best, the certificate guarantees uniqueness of the web site, provided that the web site itself has not been compromised (hacked) or the certificate issuing process subverted.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider can opt to issue three types of certificates, each requiring its own degree of vetting rigor.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] In order of increasing rigor (and naturally, cost) they are: Domain Validation, Organization Validation and Extended Validation.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] These rigors are loosely agreed upon by voluntary participants in the CA/Browser Forum.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider will issue a domain-validated (DV) certificate to a purchaser if the purchaser can demonstrate one vetting criterion: the right to administratively manage the affected DNS domain(s).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider will issue an organization validation (OV) class certificate to a purchaser if the purchaser can meet two criteria: the right to administratively manage the domain name in question, and perhaps, the organization's actual existence as a legal entity.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider publishes its OV vetting criteria through its certificate policy.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] To acquire an Extended Validation (EV) certificate, the purchaser must persuade the certificate provider of its legal identity, including manual verification checks by a human.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] As with OV certificates, a certificate provider publishes its EV vetting criteria through its certificate policy.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Until 2019, major browsers such as Chrome and Firefox generally offered users a visual indication of the legal identity when a site presented an EV certificate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] This was done by showing the legal name before the domain, and a bright green color to highlight the change.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Most browsers deprecated this feature providing no visual difference to the user on the type of certificate used.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] This change followed security concerns raised by forensic experts and successful attempts to purchase EV certificates to impersonate famous organizations, proving the inefficiency of these visual indicators and highlighting potential abuses.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] A web browser will give no warning to the user if a web site suddenly presents a different certificate, even if that certificate has a lower number of key bits, even if it has a different provider, and even if the previous certificate had an expiry date far into the future.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Where certificate providers are under the jurisdiction of governments, those governments may have the freedom to order the provider to generate any certificate, such as for the purposes of law enforcement.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Subsidiary wholesale certificate providers also have the freedom to generate any certificate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] All web browsers come with an extensive built-in list of trusted root certificates, many of which are controlled by organizations that may be unfamiliar to the user.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] Each of these organizations is free to issue any certificate for any web site and have the guarantee that web browsers that include its root certificates will accept it as genuine.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] In this instance, end users must rely on the developer of the browser software to manage its built-in list of certificates and on the certificate providers to behave correctly and to inform the browser developer of problematic certificates.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] While uncommon, there have been incidents in which fraudulent certificates have been issued: in some cases, the browsers have detected the fraud; in others, some time passed before browser developers removed these certificates from their software.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] The list of built-in certificates is also not limited to those provided by the browser developer: users (and to a degree applications) are free to extend the list for special purposes such as for company intranets.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] This means that if someone gains access to a machine and can install a new root certificate in the browser, that browser will recognize websites that use the inserted certificate as legitimate.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] For provable security, this reliance on something external to the system has the consequence that any public-key certification scheme has to rely on some special setup assumption, such as the existence of a certificate authority.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] In spite of the limitations described above, certificate-authenticated TLS is considered mandatory by all security guidelines whenever a web site hosts confidential information or performs material transactions.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/public-key-certificate] This is because, in practice, in spite of the weaknesses described above, web sites secured by public-key certificates are still more secure than unsecured http:// web sites.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI replaces the BIOS that was present in the boot ROM of all personal computers that are IBM PC compatible, although it can provide backwards compatibility with the BIOS using CSM booting.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Unlike the BIOS, which was originally developed by IBM as a proprietary architecture, the UEFI specification is managed by an industry consortium.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Most production firmware implementations for both remain proprietary.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Intel developed the original *Extensible Firmware Interface* (*EFI*) specification.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The last Intel version of EFI was 1.10 released in 2005.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Subsequent versions have been developed as UEFI by the UEFI Forum.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI is independent of platform and programming language, but C is used for the reference implementation TianoCore EDKII.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The original motivation for EFI came during early development of the first Intel–HP Itanium systems in the mid-1990s.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] BIOS limitations had become too restrictive for the larger server platforms for which Itanium was targeted.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The effort to address these concerns began in 1998 and was initially called *Intel Boot Initiative*.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] It was later renamed to *Extensible Firmware Interface* (EFI).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The first open-source UEFI implementation, Tiano, was released by Intel in 2004.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Tiano has since then been superseded by EDK and EDK II and is now maintained by the TianoCore community.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In July 2008, Intel ceased its development of the EFI specification at version 1.10 and contributed it to the Unified EFI Forum, which has developed the specification as the *Unified Extensible Firmware Interface* (UEFI).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The original EFI specification remains owned by Intel, which exclusively provides licenses for EFI-based products, but the UEFI specification is owned by the UEFI Forum.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Version 2.0 of the UEFI specification was released on 31 January 2006.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Version 2.1 of the UEFI specification was released on 7 January 2007.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] It added network authentication and the user interface architecture ("Human Interface Infrastructure" in UEFI).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Version 2.3.1 of the UEFI specification was released on 6 April 2011.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] It added Secure Boot, as well as ARM architecture support.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In October 2018, Arm introduced Arm ServerReady, a compliance certification program intended to ensure standard operating systems and hypervisors run on Arm-based servers.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The program requires the system firmware to comply with Server Base Boot Requirements (SBBR).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] SBBR requires UEFI, ACPI and SMBIOS compliance.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In October 2020, Arm announced the extension of the program to the edge and IoT market.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The new program name is Arm SystemReady.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Many Linux and BSD distributions can support both recipes.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In December 2018, Microsoft announced Project Mu, a fork of TianoCore EDK II used in Microsoft Surface and Hyper-V products.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The project incorporates a service-based firmware delivery model.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The latest UEFI specification, version 2.11, was published in December 2024.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI supports processor architectures that are 32-bit or higher.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] However, only processors with a little-endian mode are supported.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Unofficial UEFI support is under development for POWERPC64 by implementing TianoCore EDK II on top of OPAL, the OpenPOWER abstraction layer, running in little-endian mode.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For MIPS, there also exists an unofficial project, based on the original EDK.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] However, both projects have since been abandoned as of November 2016 and September 2015 respectively.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI only allows executing UEFI applications that match the firmware's bit-width, even if the processor supports smaller or larger bit-widths.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For example, a 64-bit UEFI firmware may only execute 64-bit UEFI applications, even if the processor has a 32-bit processor mode.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Some low-end computers have been shipped with 32-bit UEFI firmware running on 64-bit CPUs.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Once a UEFI application ends the boot services and gets granted full control over the system, it becomes possible to change the processor execution mode.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] However, calling runtime services requires shortly changing back to the original processor mode, as runtime services may only be called from the same processor mode as the firmware implementation.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The Linux kernel added support for booting 64-bit kernels on 32-bit UEFI firmware implementations with x86-64 CPUs since version 3.15, requiring the UEFI boot loader to support the EFI handover protocol.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The EFI handover protocol allows UEFI boot loaders to defer the UEFI initialization to the kernel's EFI boot stub, so that only the kernel does the UEFI initialization.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In addition to the standard PC disk partition scheme that uses a master boot record (MBR), UEFI also works with the GUID Partition Table (GPT) partitioning scheme, which is free from many of the limitations of MBR.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In particular, the MBR limits on the number and size of disk partitions (up to four primary partitions per disk, and up to 2 TB (2 × 240 bytes) per disk) are relaxed.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] More specifically, GPT allows for a maximum disk and partition size of 8 ZiB (8 × 270 bytes) with 512 byte sectors.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The UEFI specification only supports FAT12/16/32 partitions that are on GPT or MBR disks as well as El Torito-formatted optical discs.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Although GPT is a part of the UEFI standard, it may also be usable by BIOS PCs to boot an operating system off of.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Support for GPT in Linux is enabled by turning on the option `CONFIG_EFI_PARTITION` (EFI GUID Partition Support) during kernel configuration.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This option allows Linux to recognize and use GPT disks after the system firmware passes control over the system to Linux.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For reverse compatibility, Linux can use GPT disks in BIOS-based systems for both data storage and booting, as both GRUB 2 and Linux are GPT-aware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Such a setup is usually referred to as *BIOS-GPT*.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] As GPT incorporates the protective MBR, a BIOS-based computer can boot from a GPT disk using a GPT-aware boot loader stored in the protective MBR's bootstrap code area.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In the case of GRUB, such a configuration requires a BIOS boot partition for GRUB to embed its second-stage code due to absence of the post-MBR gap in GPT partitioned disks (which is taken over by the GPT's *Primary Header* and *Primary Partition Table*).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Commonly 1 MB in size, this partition's Globally Unique Identifier (GUID) in GPT scheme is 21686148-6449-6E6F-744E-656564454649 and is used by GRUB only in BIOS-GPT setups.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] From GRUB's perspective, no such partition type exists in case of MBR partitioning.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This partition is not required if the system is UEFI-based because no embedding of the second-stage code is needed in that case.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI systems can access GPT disks and boot directly from them, which allows Linux to use UEFI boot methods.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Booting Linux from GPT disks on UEFI systems involves creation of an EFI system partition (ESP), which contains UEFI applications such as bootloaders, operating system kernels, and utility software.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Such a setup is usually referred to as *UEFI-GPT*, while ESP is recommended to be at least 512 MB in size and formatted with a FAT32 filesystem for maximum compatibility.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For backward compatibility, some UEFI implementations also support booting from MBR-partitioned disks through the Compatibility Support Module (CSM) that provides legacy BIOS compatibility.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In that case, booting Linux on UEFI systems is the same as on legacy BIOS-based systems.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Windows 11, 64-bit versions of Windows Vista SP1/SP2 and 7, and both 32-bit and 64-bit versions of Windows 8, 8.1, and 10 can boot from a GPT disk that is larger than 2 TB.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] EFI defines two types of services: *boot services* and *runtime services*.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Boot services are available only while the firmware owns the platform (i.e., before the `ExitBootServices()` call), and they include text and graphical consoles on various devices, and bus, block and file services.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Runtime services are still accessible while the operating system is running; they include services such as date, time and NVRAM access.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI variables provide a way to store data, in particular non-volatile data.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Some UEFI variables are shared between platform firmware and operating systems.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Variable namespaces are identified by GUIDs, and variables are key/value pairs.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] after a crash for the operating system to retrieve after a reboot.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI executes independent programs known as UEFI applications, which are stored as files on the EFI system partition.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] These can be launched via the UEFI Shell, the firmware boot manager, or other UEFI applications, and may be developed independently of the original equipment manufacturer (OEM).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] A type of UEFI application is an OS boot loader such as GRUB, rEFInd, systemd-boot, and Windows Boot Manager, which loads some OS files into memory and executes them.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Also, an OS boot loader can provide a user interface to allow the selection of another UEFI application to run.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Utilities like the UEFI Shell are also UEFI applications.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] EFI defines protocols as a set of software interfaces used for communication between two binary modules.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] All EFI drivers must provide services to others via protocols.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The EFI Protocols are similar to the BIOS interrupt calls.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In addition to standard instruction set architecture-specific device drivers, EFI provides for an ISA-independent device driver stored in non-volatile memory as *EFI byte code* or *EBC*.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] System firmware has an interpreter for EBC images.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In that sense, EBC is analogous to Open Firmware, the ISA-independent firmware used in PowerPC-based Apple Macintosh and Sun Microsystems SPARC computers, among others.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Some architecture-specific (non-EFI Byte Code) EFI drivers for some device types can have interfaces for use by the OS.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This allows the OS to rely on EFI for drivers to perform basic graphics and network functions before, and if, operating-system-specific drivers are loaded.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In other cases, the EFI driver can be filesystem drivers that allow for booting from other types of disk volumes.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Examples include *efifs* for 37 file systems (based on GRUB2 code), used by Rufus for chain-loading NTFS ESPs.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The EFI 1.0 specification defined a UGA (Universal Graphic Adapter) protocol as a way to support graphics features.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI did not include UGA and replaced it with GOP (Graphics Output Protocol).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI 2.1 defined a "Human Interface Infrastructure" (HII) to manage user input, localized strings, fonts, and forms (in the HTML sense).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] These enable original equipment manufacturers (OEMs) or independent BIOS vendors (IBVs) to design graphical interfaces for pre-boot configuration.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI uses UTF-16 to encode strings by default; since at least UEFI 2.4, it allows using ASCII to encode ASCII-only strings.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Most early UEFI firmware implementations were console-based.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Today many UEFI firmware implementations are GUI-based.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] An EFI system partition, often abbreviated to ESP, is a data storage device partition that is used in computers adhering to the UEFI specification.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Accessed by the UEFI firmware when a computer is powered up, it stores UEFI applications and the files these applications need to run, including operating system boot loaders.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Supported partition table schemes include MBR and GPT, as well as El Torito volumes on optical discs.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] For use on ESPs, UEFI defines a specific version of the FAT file system, which is maintained as part of the UEFI specification and independently from the original FAT specification, encompassing the FAT32, FAT16 and FAT12 file systems.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The ESP also provides space for a boot sector as part of the backward BIOS compatibility.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Computers are started up by a process which has been called booting: the computer loads its operating software by means of a very small program built into the hardware, which typically loads a program, still small, to load and start the operating system (OS).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Unlike the legacy PC BIOS, UEFI does not rely on boot sectors on the computer's data storage, defining instead a boot manager as part of the UEFI specification.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] When a computer is powered on, the boot manager checks the boot configuration and, based on its settings, then executes the specified OS boot loader or operating system kernel.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The boot configuration is defined by variables stored in the computer's persistent NVRAM storage, including variables that indicate the file system paths to OS loaders or OS kernels.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] OS boot loaders can be automatically detected by UEFI, which enables easy booting from removable devices such as USB flash drives.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This automated detection relies on standardized file paths to the OS boot loader, with the path varying depending on the computer architecture.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The format of the file path is defined as <EFI_SYSTEM_PARTITION>\EFI\BOOT\BOOT<MACHINE_TYPE_SHORT_NAME>.EFI; for example, the file path to the OS loader on an x86-64 system is \efi\boot\bootx64.efi, and \efi\boot\bootaa64.efi on ARM64 architecture.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Booting UEFI systems from GPT-partitioned disks is commonly called *UEFI-GPT booting*, although the UEFI specification requires MBR partition tables to be fully supported.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Some UEFI firmware implementations immediately switch to BIOS-based CSM booting depending on the type of the boot disk's partition table, effectively preventing UEFI booting from an EFI System Partition on MBR-partitioned disks; such a boot scheme is commonly called *UEFI-MBR*.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] It is also common for a boot manager to have a textual user interface to allow the user to select the desired OS (or setup utility) from a list of available boot options.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] On PC platforms, firmware supporting UEFI boot is often referred to as a "UEFI BIOS", though some newer x86 platforms exclude CSM support entirely.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] To ensure backward compatibility, UEFI firmware implementations on PC-class machines could support booting in legacy BIOS mode from MBR-partitioned disks through the Compatibility Support Module (CSM) that provides legacy BIOS compatibility.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In this scenario, booting is performed in the same way as on legacy BIOS-based systems, by ignoring the partition table and relying on the content of a boot sector.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The Compatibility Support Module allows legacy operating systems and some legacy option ROMs that do not support UEFI to still be used.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] It also provides required legacy System Management Mode (SMM) functionality (CompatibilitySmm) in addition to features provided by the UEFI SMM.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] An example of such a legacy SMM functionality is providing USB legacy support for keyboard and mouse, by emulating their classic PS/2 counterparts.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In November 2017, Intel announced that it planned to phase out support CSM for client platforms by 2020.
