[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The UEFI specification defines a Secure Boot that can secure the boot process by preventing the loading of UEFI drivers or OS boot loaders that are not signed with an acceptable digital signature.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] When Secure Boot is enabled, it is initially placed in "setup" mode, which allows a public key known as the "platform key" (PK) to be written to the firmware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Once the key is written, Secure Boot enters "User" mode, where only UEFI drivers and OS boot loaders signed with the platform key can be loaded by the firmware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Additional "key exchange keys" (KEK) can be added to a database stored in memory to allow other certificates to be used, but they must still have a connection to the private portion of the platform key.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Secure Boot can also be placed in "Custom" mode, where additional public keys can be added to the system that do not match the private key.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] As of January 2025, FreeBSD support is in its planning stage.
