[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Initialization at this stage involves creating data structures in memory and establishing default values within these structures.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This stage has several components including PEI foundation, PEIMs and PPI.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Due to less resources available in this stage, this stage must be minimal and do minimal preparations for the next stage, DXE, which is richer.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] After SEC phase hand off, platform responsibility is taken by PEI Foundation.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This component is responsible for invoking PEIMs and managing their dependencies.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] These are minimal PEI drivers that are responsible for initialization of hardware components, such as permanent memory, CPU, chipset and motherboard.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Each of the PEIMs have single responsibilities and focus on single initialization.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] These drivers come from different vendors.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This is a data structure that composed of GUID pairs of pointers.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] PPIs are discovered by PEIMs through PEI services.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] After minimal initialization of the system for DXE, PEI foundation locates and passes control to DXE.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The PEI foundation dispatches DXE foundation through special PPI called IPL (Initial Program Load).
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This stage consists of C modules and a dependency-aware dispatcher.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] With main memory now available, CPU, chipset, mainboard and other I/O devices are initialized in DXE and BDS.
