[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] UEFI implementation flaws have been exploited to gain persistence, the ability to maintain malicious access to a compromised system even after system reboot, operating system reinstallation, and even partial physical part replacement, such as of corrupted PCI persistent flash storage.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] There were vulnerabilities in 2023 even with Secure Boot enabled.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In 2023 Microsoft published a warning about BlackLotus UEFI malware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Numerous digital rights activists have protested UEFI.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Minnich, a co-author of coreboot, and Cory Doctorow, a digital rights activist, have criticized UEFI as an attempt to remove the ability of the user to truly control the computer.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Critics, such as coreboot co-author Ronald G.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Minnich, argue that UEFI maintains the historic arrangement of requiring two separate drivers—one for the firmware and one for the operating system—for most hardware.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Open-source project TianoCore also provides UEFIs.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] TianoCore lacks the specialized firmware drivers and modules that initialize chipset functions, but TianoCore is one of many payload options of coreboot.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] The development of coreboot requires cooperation from chipset manufacturers to provide the specifications needed to develop initialization drivers.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In 2011, Microsoft announced that computers certified to run its Windows 8 operating system had to ship with Microsoft's public key enrolled and Secure Boot enabled, which implies that using UEFI is a requirement for these devices.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Following the announcement, critics and free-software/open-source advocates, including the Free Software Foundation, expressed concern that Microsoft might use the Secure Boot functionality of UEFI to restrict the installation of alternative operating systems such as Linux.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Microsoft denied that the Secure Boot requirement was intended to serve as a form of lock-in and clarified its requirements by stating that x86-based systems certified for Windows 8 must allow Secure Boot to enter custom mode or be disabled, but not on systems using the ARM architecture.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Windows 10 allows OEMs to decide whether or not Secure Boot can be managed by users of their x86 systems.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Other developers raised concerns about the legal and practical issues of implementing support for Secure Boot on Linux systems in general.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Other developers suggested that signed builds of Linux with another key could be provided, but noted that it would be difficult to persuade OEMs to ship their computers with the required key alongside the Microsoft key.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Several major Linux distributions have developed different implementations for Secure Boot.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Garrett himself developed a minimal bootloader known as a shim, which is a precompiled, signed bootloader that allows the user to individually trust keys provided by Linux distributions.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] That also allows users to build their own kernels and use custom kernel modules as well, without the need to reconfigure the system.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Fedora also uses shim, but requires that both the kernel and its modules be signed as well. shim has Machine Owner Key (MOK) that can be used to sign locally compiled kernels and other software not signed by distribution maintainer, without changing the Secure Boot mode to setup mode.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In Windows, if Secure Boot is enabled, all kernel drivers must be digitally signed; non-WHQL drivers may be refused to load.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In February 2013, another Red Hat developer attempted to submit a patch to the Linux kernel that would allow it to parse Microsoft's authenticode signing using a master X.509 key embedded in PE files signed by Microsoft.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] However, the proposal was criticized by Linux creator Linus Torvalds, who argued that Red Hat was accommodating Microsoft's control over the Secure Boot infrastructure.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] On 26 March 2013, the Spanish free-software development group Hispalinux filed a formal complaint with the European Commission, contending that Microsoft's Secure Boot requirements on OEM systems were "obstructive" and anti-competitive.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] At the Black Hat conference in August 2013, a group of security researchers presented a series of exploits in specific vendor implementations of UEFI that could be used to exploit Secure Boot.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] In August 2016 it was reported that two security researchers had found the "golden key" security key Microsoft uses in signing operating systems.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] Technically, no key was exposed, but an exploitable binary signed by the key was.
[src:uefi-secure-boot-deep/unified-extensible-firmware-interface] This allows software to execute as though it were signed by Microsoft, presenting potential risks for rootkit and bootkit attacks.
